<br>
<br>
Heh...  I know that feeling.<br>
<br>
Everyone sees roleplay as something unique.  I doubt any two people see it as just the same thing.  Also every persons idea of what is roleplaying changes with time and enviroment.<br>
<br>
Take myself for example:  After playing a text-based roleplaying enforced (not just &quot;encouraged&quot;) game called DragonRealms for years nothing in EverQuest even seemed remotely close to roleplay.   But after time (a couple years or so playing EverQuest on a &quot;normal&quot; server) you grow accustomed to the OOC terms and actions.  At one point I use to consider myself a fair roleplayer, now I find myself struggling.<br>
<br>
Note:  And to the player of the character who heard one particular bad OOC outburst from me I appologize.  Their is no excuse but to explain why I was rather upset about spending over four hours patching (just after SOL) just to log in and see a server going down message.<br>
<br>
Anyway...  I think the point is that some roleplayers seem to look for infractions to pounce on, when what is needed is to be a little tolerant of what each considers roleplay.   And moreso because even the best roleplayer is going to mess up sometimes.<br>
<br>
*shrug*  Just my thoughts on it.<br>
<br>
<br>
